Generates minimal test sequences for the programmatic expansion space — exercising every construct's base form, deep nesting, multi-arity generics, fused returns, partial fills, and invalid inputs. The reference walker (D9) runs over these sequences to validate that the C++ dictionary stays synchronized with the expansion rules.

The `Palette` struct collects type strokes by arity (concrete, arity-1, arity-2) from the corpus; `from()` returns `None` if no concrete types exist, causing `sample_sequences` to emit an empty sequence set. `terminal_fill(c, p)` produces a construct's minimal fill by appending one concrete type per slot, merging the first into the shape if the construct is fused (via `merge_strokes`); it returns `None` if a fused merge fails, halting that construct's sampling.

`push_construct_fills` emits both the full fill and a one-stroke-short partial. `push_deep` finds the first standalone emitter (unfused, single slot, non-empty base) and generates nesting depths 1–3, a mid-obligation partial, an arity-2 sequence, and a fused generic return. `push_fused_generic` requires a generic stroke (arity-1), a fused construct with one return slot, and a successful merge of the generic into the shape. `push_negatives` adds an unmatched base stroke and an over-filled valid construct (type stroke beyond what slots require) to test rejection paths.